Here is one approach.

**Setup**

First, set up some maps to map between encoded and non-encoded values. The map types for encoding and decoding are different to facilitate each method in which they are used.
```
static Map&lt;Character, Byte&gt; dnaToCode =
        Map.of(&#39;A&#39;, (byte) 0, &#39;G&#39;, (byte) 2, &#39;C&#39;, (byte) 1, &#39;T&#39;, (byte) 3);
static Map&lt;Integer, String&gt; codeToDna =
		Map.of(0, &quot;A&quot;, 2, &quot;G&quot;, 1, &quot;C&quot;, 3, &quot;T&quot;);
````
**Encoding**

The general idea is to iterate over the `dna` strand, map the nucleotide to its 2 bit equivalent, converting every pair to a hex digit and return the string.

- define a string for converstion to hex
- define a few types for storage and processing
- Since every two nucleotides equate to one hex digit, increment the loop by two.
- assign the first bit pair to a byte variable
- shift left two bits for the next encoding.
- check to see if the end has been reached (and odd strand length). If so, skip it.
- else store next value and append a hex digit.
- then insert a delimiter based on the value of `i` (between every hex pairing).
- return the strand length prepended to the encoding.
```
static String hexDigits = &quot;0123456789ABCDEF&quot;;
	
public static String encode(String dna) {
	StringBuilder encoded = new StringBuilder();
	char[] n = dna.toCharArray();
	int len = dna.length();
	
	for (int i = 0; i &lt; len; i += 2) {
		byte b = dnaToCode.get(n[i]);
		b &lt;&lt;= 2;
		if (i &lt; len - 1) {
			b |= dnaToCode.get(n[i + 1]);
		}
		encoded.append(hexDigits.charAt(b));
		if (i % 4 == 2) {
			encoded.append(&quot; &quot;);
		}
	}
	return len + &quot; &quot; + encoded.toString();
}
```
**Decoding**

- to decode, just split on the white space.
- then grab the length as the first array element.
- for the rest, simply process two hex digits at a time, shifting and ANDing and using the other map to get the nucleotide for the encoding.
- the conditional checks for single digit hex tokens.
- then return the string which is adjusted for the actual length of the strand.
```	
public static String decode(String code) {
	String[] s = code.split(&quot; &quot;);
	int len = Integer.parseInt(s[0]);

	StringBuilder decoded = new StringBuilder();
	for (int i = 1; i &lt; s.length; i++) {
		int val = Integer.parseInt(s[i], 16);
		if (s[i].length() &gt; 1) {
			decoded.append(codeToDna.get(val &gt;&gt; 6));
			decoded.append(codeToDna.get((val &gt;&gt; 4) &amp; 3));
		}
		decoded.append(codeToDna.get((val &gt;&gt; 2) &amp; 3));
		decoded.append(codeToDna.get(val &amp; 3));
	}
	return decoded.toString().substring(0,len);
}
```
